S1.T1.caption: TABLE I: Summary of the differences with highly related papers.
S1.T1.table:
Articles combining FL and DRL
[22]: Decoupled setting: hierarchical nested personalized FL for stratified UAVs swarms; DRL for swarm trajectory and learning duration design. Ours: Integrated setting: Direct enhancement of decentralized multi-agent DRL by FL.
[23]: Single-agent DRL-based device selection for asynchronous FL.
[24]: Targeting at the data heterogeneity issue of multi-agent DRL by imposing KL divergence-based penalty term. Ours: Targeting at the learning inefficiency issue of multi-agent DRL by decay and consensus-based FL methods.
Decay-based Method
[19]: Decaying the learning rate of different epochs. Ours: Decaying the weights of different mini-bathes within one period.
[25]: Assuming an off-line available set of data points and assigning aggregation weights according to their sizes. No consideration of the resource cost. Ours: On-line DRL tasks and assigning time-decreasing aggregation weights regardless of data sizes.
Consensus-based Method
[26, 27, 28]: Disabled central-serverâ€™s functionality and only consensus-based aggregation of different agentsâ€™ gradients. Ours: Hierarchical configuration with both the agent-server interaction and agentsâ€™ mutual interaction.
[21]: Convergence result with respect to the spectral radius of the network topology. Ours: Convergence result with respect to the algebraic connectivity of the network topology.
references:
Taking account of the modelâ€™s error convergence bound with respect to the mainly required communication and computation overheads during the training phase, this paper proposes a system utility function-based metric to evaluate the effectiveness of different optimization methods for federated IRL (FIRL). Furthermore, in order to improve the systemâ€™s utility value, this paper develops two new optimization methods (i.e., the decay-based and consensus-based methods) on top of the variation-aware periodic averaging (VPA) method.
In particular, since the variance of modelâ€™s gradients gradually increases along with the progress of local updating, the decay-based method utilizes a discrete periodic decay function to decrease the weights of a modelâ€™s successive local gradients within one period, which also contrasts with the adoption of decaying learning rates for multiple epochs in [19]. We concretely provide a practical implementation of this decay-based method with an exponential decay function and theoretically demonstrate its superior effectiveness. On the other hand, the consensus-based method introduces the consensus algorithm [20] into both IRL and FL, where agents are allowed to exchange their local gradients with neighbors directly before performing local updates. Different from the spectral radius-based theoretical analyses in [21], this paper obtains the consensus-based methodâ€™s error convergence bound dependent on the algebraic connectivity of the graph comprised by agents and their connections. We theoretically show that the consensus-based method can reduce the modelâ€™s error convergence bound dramatically and speed up the learning process. Table I summarizes the key differences with highly related works. Finally, through an MARL simulation scenario, we demonstrate the superiority of these two developed methods in terms of the modelâ€™s convergence performance and systemâ€™s utility value.
